nvert|120|mm|in|abbr=on}}]]/45 [[Caliber|cal]] DP guns\n*6 \u00d7 Type 96 [[Type 96 25&nbsp;mm AT/AA Gun|Type 96 {{convert|25|mm|in|abbr=on}}]] AA machine guns (2\u00d73)\n*12 \u00d7 Type 3 depth charge throwers\n*1 \u00d7 depth charge chute\n*120 \u00d7 [[depth charge]]s\n*1 \u00d7 [[Type 97 81 mm infantry mortar|{{convert|81|mm|in|abbr=on}}]] mortar\n|Ship armour=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''CD-202''''' or '''''No. 202''''' was a [[Type D escort ship]] of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] during [[World War II]].\n\n==History==\nShe was laid down on 16 February 1945 at the [[Nagasaki]] shipyard of [[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]] for the benefit of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] and launched on 2 April 1945.<ref name=CFCD-202>{{cite web |url=http://www.combinedfleet.com/CD-202_t.htm|title=Kakyakusen: IJN Escort CD-202: Tabular Record of Movement|first1=Bob |last1=Hackett |first2= Kingsepp  |last2=Sander  |first3=Peter |last3=Cundall |first4=Tatsuhiro   |last4=Higuchi |work=combinedfleet.com |year=2012 |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Stille>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TGErDwAAQBAJ&q=cd-202#v=snippet&q=cd-202&f=false|first=Mark |last=Stille|authorlink=|title=Imperial Japanese Navy Antisubmarine Escorts 1941-45|pages=41\u201345 |publisher=[[Bloomsbury Press]]|date=July 18, 2017|ISBN=9781472818164}}</ref> On 7 July 1945, she was completed and commissioned.<ref name=CFCD-202/><ref name=Stille/> On 15 August 1945, Japan announced their [[Surrender of Japan|unconditional surrender]] and ''CD-202'' traveled to [[Sasebo, Nagasaki|Sasebo]] where on 17 August 1945, a steam pipe exploded killing one man.<ref name=CFCD-202/> On 30 November 1945, she was struck from the Navy List.<ref name=CFCD-202/> She was scrapped in 1947.<ref name=Stille/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:CD-202}}\n[[Category:1945 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Japan]]\n[[Category:Type D escort ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built by Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]]