{"title_page": "2020 in aviation", "text_new": "{{yearbox\n|in?=in aviation\n|cp=20th century\n|c=21st century \n|cf=22nd century\n|yp1=2017\n|yp2=2018\n|yp3=2019\n|year=2020\n|ya1=2021\n|ya2=2022\n|ya3=2023\n|dp3=1990s\n|dp2=2000s (decade){{!}}2000s\n|dp1=2010s (decade){{!}}2010s\n|d=2020\u20132029{{!}}2020s\n|dn1=2010s\n|dn2=2020s\n|dn3=2030s\n}}\n{{Portal|Aviation|Modern history}}\n\n2020 in aviation\n\n==Events==\n\n=== January ===\n\n; 2 January\n: A [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk]] helicopter operated by the [[Republic of China Air Force]] (ROCAF) [[2020 New Taipei helicopter crash|crashes]] in the [[Wulai District]] in [[New Taipei City]], [[Taiwan]]. Eight people are killed, including Taiwan's [[Chief of the General Staff (Republic of China)|Chief of the General Staff]], Gen. [[Shen Yi-ming]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=231864|title=Accident Sikorsky UH-60M Black Hawk 933, 02 Jan 2020|last=Ranter|first=Harro|website=aviation-safety.net|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n; 8 January\n: A [[Boeing 737-800]] operating as [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]] from [[Tehran]], Iran to [[Kiev]], Ukraine, crashes shortly after takeoff from [[Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport]], killing all 167 passengers and 9 crew.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Ukrainian Boeing plane crashes in Iran, 176 people dead|url=https://edition.cnn.com/middleeast/live-news/iran-plane-crash-live-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> Iran subsequently admits that the aircraft was mistakenly shot down by a surface-to-air missile.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iran admits 'unintentionally' shooting down plane |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51073621 |date=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 9 January\n: A [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] operated by the [[South African Air Force]] from [[Beni, Democratic Republic of the Congo|Beni]] to [[Goma]] in the Democratic Republic of the Congo crashes upon landing at [[Goma International Airport]]. A fire which broke out on the left engine upon landing was contained and all 59 passengers and 8 crew members were safely evacuated with no casualties.<ref>{{citeweb|title=UN: South African military plane crash-lands in Congo|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/africa/un-south-african-military-plane-crash-lands-in-congo-1.614136|publisher=Stars and Stripes|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 23 January\n: A [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] operated by [[New South Wales Rural Fire Service]] crashed while fighting bushfires near [[Cooma]], [[New South Wales]] in Australia. Three United States personnel were killed in the accident.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Three dead as air tanker fighting bushfires crashes near Snowy Mountains|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/air-tanker-fighting-bushfires-reportedly-crashes-in-snowy-mountains-20200123-p53u3r.html|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|title=Three firefighters dead after Large Air Tanker crashes while fighting bushfires in southern NSW|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/nsw-rfs-air-tanker-crashes-near-numeralla-bushfire/11893554?pfmredir=sm|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n: China starts shutting down regular air traffic to and from [[Wuhan Airport]] in [[Hubei|Hubei province]] due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Jakob Wert | title = China shuts down Wuhan Airport amid virus outbreak | newspaper = International Flight Network | date = 23 January 2020 | url = https://www.ifn.news/posts/china-shuts-down-wuhan-airport-amid-virus-outbreak/ | accessdate = 5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 25 January\n: The [[Boeing 777X]] takes off from [[Paine Field]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] on its first ever flight lasting roughly three hours.<ref name=Boeing25jan2020>{{cite press release |url= https://investors.boeing.com/investors/investor-news/press-release-details/2020/New-Boeing-777X-Completes-Successful-First-Flight/default.aspx |title= New Boeing 777X Completes Successful First Flight |date= January 25, 2020 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref>\n\n; 26 January\n: [[Caspian Airlines Flight 6936]], a McDonnell Douglas MD-83, overruns the runway on landing at Mahshahr Airport, Iran, landing on a road beyond the runway. All 144 passengers and crew survive.\n\n; 27 January \n: An [[Bombardier_Global_Express#Military_variants|E-11A]], a [[United States Air Force]] plane, [[Deh Yak airplane crash|crashed]] in the [[Dih Yak District]], [[Ghazni Province]], Afghanistan. At least two people were killed.<ref name=AH>{{cite web |url=http://avherald.com/h?article=4d282570&opt=0 |title=No Afghan Ariana Airlines Crash |first=Simon |last=Hradecky |publisher=Aviation Herald |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 28 January\n: At the [[Heli-Expo]] convention in Anaheim, California, Italian helicopter manufacturer [[Leonardo S.p.A.|Leonardo]] announces it will acquire Swiss helicopter company [[Kopter]] (320 people), developer of the single-engined [[Kopter SH09]], for at least $185 million in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/hai-heli-expo-2020/leonardo-acquires-kopter-in-a-deal-worth-at-least-185m/136406.article |title= Leonardo acquires Kopter in a deal worth at least $185m |author= Pilar Wolfsteller |date= 28 January 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n; 29 January\n: [[Boeing]] releases its fourth quarter 2019 earnings report, including data for the full 12 months of 2019. The company made an annual loss for the first time since 1997.<ref>{{cite news | author = Jakob Wert | title = Boeing posts first annual loss since 1997 in 2019 earnings | newspaper = International Flight Network | date = 29 January 2020 | url = https://www.ifn.news/posts/boeing-posts-first-annual-loss-since-1997-in-2019-earnings/ | accessdate = 5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n; 5 February\n: A Boeing 737-800 operating [[Pegasus Airlines Flight 2193]] from [[\u0130zmir Adnan Menderes Airport|Izmir]] skids off the runway on landing at [[Istanbul Sabiha G\u00f6k\u00e7en International Airport]], and breaks into pieces. Three people were killed and 179 injured.<ref>{{cite news |title=Three dead, 179 hurt as plane skids off runway |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51384667 |work=BBC News |date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 12 February\n: [[Bombardier Aviation|Bombardier]] exits the commercial aviation business, selling its share in the [[Airbus A220|A220]] programme to Airbus for $591 million.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Airbus and the Government of Qu\u00e9bec become sole owners of the A220 Programme as Bombardier completes its strategic exit from Commercial Aviation |url=https://ir.bombardier.com/en/press-releases/press-releases/86019-airbus-and-the-government-of-quebec-become-sole-owners-of-the-a220-programme-as-bombardier-completes-its-strategic-exit-from-commercial-aviation |website=ir.bombardier.com |publisher=Bombardier Inc. |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 17 February\n: The solar-powered [[Persistent High Altitude Solar Aircraft|PHASA]]-35 [[Atmospheric satellite|HAPS]] built by [[BAE Systems]] makes its [[maiden flight]] from the [[Woomera Test Range]] in South Australia.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/aerospace/bae-joins-high-altitude-race-with-maiden-phasa-35-flight/136767.article |title= BAE joins high-altitude race with maiden PHASA-35 flight |author= Dan Thisdell |date= 17 February 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n; 5 March \n: UK regional carrier [[Flybe]] ceases operations of its 60 [[Q400]] and [[E-Jet]]s, and files for administration after the UK government rejected a \u00a3100 million ($129 million) loan, amid the [[COVID-19 outbreak]].<ref name=Flight5march2020>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/airlines/beleaguered-flybe-ceases-operations/137095.article |title= Beleaguered Flybe ceases operations |author= Alfred Chua |date= 5 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n; 11 March\n: Due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]], US President [[Donald Trump]] announces a travel ban from Europe's [[Schengen area]] to the United States from 13 March, for 30 days.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/air-transport/us-bans-travel-from-europe/137206.article |title= US bans all travel from Europe |author= Pilar Wolfsteller |date= 12 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> Numerous other countries implement similar bans in the following days.\n\n; 17 March\n: [[Trans States Airlines]] announces it will shut down operations on 1 April amid the coronavirus crisis, nine months earlier than previously planned due to a pilot shortage and consolidation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/strategy/trans-states-airlines-to-fold-in-april/137349.article |title= Trans States Airlines to fold in April |author= Pilar Wolfsteller |date= 17 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n; 18 March\n: The average daily number of flights in [[Eurocontrol]] airspace falls below half that of the previous year, due to [[travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/air-transport/european-flight-activity-halves-under-coronavirus-onslaught/137446.article |title= European flight activity halves under coronavirus onslaught |author= David Kaminski-Morrow |date= 20 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n; 19 March\n: [[Compass Airlines (North America)|Compass Airlines]], owned by Trans States Holdings and flying regional routes for [[American Airlines]] as [[American Eagle (airline brand)|American Eagle]] from Los Angeles, writes to its employees it will shut down completely on 7 April.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/strategy/compass-airlines-to-shut-down-operations/137408.article |title= Compass Airlines to shut down operations |author= Pilar Wolfsteller |date= 19 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\n\n; 15 April\n: As demand continues to collapse due to the [[impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on aviation]], over two-thirds of the worldwide fleet of 22,000 mainline passenger airliners are inactive, leaving 7,635 in operation.<!--ref name=Flight15apr2020--> Europe is most affected, with less than 15% of aircraft operating, compared to 45% in North America and 49% in Asia.<!--ref name=Flight15apr2020--> A greater proportion of [[narrowbody aircraft]] are inactive (37%) than [[widebody aircraft]] (27%).<ref name=Flight15apr2020>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/fleets/mixed-fortunes-globally-as-active-fleet-drops-towards-7000-aircraft/137893.article |title= Mixed fortunes globally as active fleet drops towards 7,000 aircraft |author= Max Kingsley-Jones |date= 15 April 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Aviation timelines navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in aviation| ]]\n[[Category:Aviation by year]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020-related timelines]]\n[[Category:Technology timelines by year]]\n[[Category:Transport timelines by year]]\n", "text_old": "{{yearbox\n|in?=in aviation\n|cp=20th century\n|c=21st century \n|cf=22nd century\n|yp1=2017\n|yp2=2018\n|yp3=2019\n|year=2020\n|ya1=2021\n|ya2=2022\n|ya3=2023\n|dp3=1990s\n|dp2=2000s (decade){{!}}2000s\n|dp1=2010s (decade){{!}}2010s\n|d=2020\u20132029{{!}}2020s\n|dn1=2010s\n|dn2=2020s\n|dn3=2030s\n}}\n{{Portal|Aviation|Modern history}}\n\n2020 in aviation\n\n==Events==\n\n=== January ===\n\n; 2 January\n: A [[Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk]] helicopter operated by the [[Republic of China Air Force]] (ROCAF) [[2020 New Taipei helicopter crash|crashes]] in the [[Wulai District]] in [[New Taipei City]], [[Taiwan]]. Eight people are killed, including Taiwan's [[Chief of the General Staff (Republic of China)|Chief of the General Staff]], Gen. [[Shen Yi-ming]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviation-safety.net/wikibase/wiki.php?id=231864|title=Accident Sikorsky UH-60M Black Hawk 933, 02 Jan 2020|last=Ranter|first=Harro|website=aviation-safety.net|access-date=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n; 8 January\n: A [[Boeing 737-800]] operating as [[Ukraine International Airlines Flight 752]] from [[Tehran]], Iran to [[Kiev]], Ukraine, crashes shortly after takeoff from [[Tehran Imam Khomeini International Airport]], killing all 167 passengers and 9 crew.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Ukrainian Boeing plane crashes in Iran, 176 people dead|url=https://edition.cnn.com/middleeast/live-news/iran-plane-crash-live-intl-hnk/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref> Iran subsequently admits that the aircraft was mistakenly shot down by a surface-to-air missile.<ref>{{cite news |title=Iran admits 'unintentionally' shooting down plane |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-51073621 |date=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 9 January\n: A [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] operated by the [[South African Air Force]] from [[Beni, Democratic Republic of the Congo|Beni]] to [[Goma]] in the Democratic Republic of the Congo crashes upon landing at [[Goma International Airport]]. A fire which broke out on the left engine upon landing was contained and all 59 passengers and 8 crew members were safely evacuated with no casualties.<ref>{{citeweb|title=UN: South African military plane crash-lands in Congo|url=https://www.stripes.com/news/africa/un-south-african-military-plane-crash-lands-in-congo-1.614136|publisher=Stars and Stripes|accessdate=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 23 January\n: A [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules]] operated by [[New South Wales Rural Fire Service]] crashed while fighting bushfires near [[Cooma]], [[New South Wales]] in Australia. Three United States personnel were killed in the accident.<ref>{{citeweb|title=Three dead as air tanker fighting bushfires crashes near Snowy Mountains|url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/nsw/air-tanker-fighting-bushfires-reportedly-crashes-in-snowy-mountains-20200123-p53u3r.html|publisher=Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{citeweb|title=Three firefighters dead after Large Air Tanker crashes while fighting bushfires in southern NSW|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-01-23/nsw-rfs-air-tanker-crashes-near-numeralla-bushfire/11893554?pfmredir=sm|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n: China starts shutting down regular air traffic to and from [[Wuhan Airport]] in [[Hubei|Hubei province]] due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite news | author = Jakob Wert | title = China shuts down Wuhan Airport amid virus outbreak | newspaper = International Flight Network | date = 23 January 2020 | url = https://www.ifn.news/posts/china-shuts-down-wuhan-airport-amid-virus-outbreak/ | accessdate = 5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 25 January\n: The [[Boeing 777X]] takes off from [[Paine Field]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]] on its first ever flight lasting roughly three hours.<ref name=Boeing25jan2020>{{cite press release |url= https://investors.boeing.com/investors/investor-news/press-release-details/2020/New-Boeing-777X-Completes-Successful-First-Flight/default.aspx |title= New Boeing 777X Completes Successful First Flight |date= January 25, 2020 |publisher= Boeing}}</ref>\n\n; 26 January\n: [[Caspian Airlines Flight 6936]], a McDonnell Douglas MD-83, overruns the runway on landing at Mahshahr Airport, Iran, landing on a road beyond the runway. All 144 passengers and crew survive.\n\n; 27 January \n: An [[Bombardier_Global_Express#Military_variants|E-11A]], a [[United States Air Force]] plane, [[Deh Yak airplane crash|crashed]] in the [[Dih Yak District]], [[Ghazni Province]], Afghanistan. At least two people were killed.<ref name=AH>{{cite web |url=http://avherald.com/h?article=4d282570&opt=0 |title=No Afghan Ariana Airlines Crash |first=Simon |last=Hradecky |publisher=Aviation Herald |accessdate=27 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 28 January\n: At the [[Heli-Expo]] convention in Anaheim, California, Italian helicopter manufacturer [[Leonardo S.p.A.|Leonardo]] announces it will acquire Swiss helicopter company [[Kopter]] (320 people), developer of the single-engined [[Kopter SH09]], for at least $185 million in 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/hai-heli-expo-2020/leonardo-acquires-kopter-in-a-deal-worth-at-least-185m/136406.article |title= Leonardo acquires Kopter in a deal worth at least $185m |author= Pilar Wolfsteller |date= 28 January 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n; 29 January\n: [[Boeing]] releases its fourth quarter 2019 earnings report, including data for the full 12 months of 2019. The company made an annual loss for the first time since 1997.<ref>{{cite news | author = Jakob Wert | title = Boeing posts first annual loss since 1997 in 2019 earnings | newspaper = International Flight Network | date = 29 January 2020 | url = https://www.ifn.news/posts/boeing-posts-first-annual-loss-since-1997-in-2019-earnings/ | accessdate = 5 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n; 5 February\n: A Boeing 737-800 operating [[Pegasus Airlines Flight 2193]] from [[\u0130zmir Adnan Menderes Airport|Izmir]] skids off the runway on landing at [[Istanbul Sabiha G\u00f6k\u00e7en International Airport]], and breaks into pieces. Three people were killed and 179 injured.<ref>{{cite news |title=Three dead, 179 hurt as plane skids off runway |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-51384667 |work=BBC News |date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 12 February\n: [[Bombardier Aviation|Bombardier]] exits the commercial aviation business, selling its share in the [[Airbus A220|A220]] programme to Airbus for $591 million.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Airbus and the Government of Qu\u00e9bec become sole owners of the A220 Programme as Bombardier completes its strategic exit from Commercial Aviation |url=https://ir.bombardier.com/en/press-releases/press-releases/86019-airbus-and-the-government-of-quebec-become-sole-owners-of-the-a220-programme-as-bombardier-completes-its-strategic-exit-from-commercial-aviation |website=ir.bombardier.com |publisher=Bombardier Inc. |accessdate=13 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n; 17 February\n: The solar-powered [[Persistent High Altitude Solar Aircraft|PHASA]]-35 [[Atmospheric satellite|HAPS]] built by [[BAE Systems]] makes its [[maiden flight]] from the [[Woomera Test Range]] in South Australia.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/aerospace/bae-joins-high-altitude-race-with-maiden-phasa-35-flight/136767.article |title= BAE joins high-altitude race with maiden PHASA-35 flight |author= Dan Thisdell |date= 17 February 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n=== March ===\n; 5 March \n: UK regional carrier [[Flybe]] ceases operations of its 60 [[Q400]] and [[E-Jet]]s, and files for administration after the UK government rejected a \u00a3100 million ($129 million) loan, amid the [[COVID-19 outbreak]].<ref name=Flight5march2020>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/airlines/beleaguered-flybe-ceases-operations/137095.article |title= Beleaguered Flybe ceases operations |author= Alfred Chua |date= 5 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n; 11 March\n: Due to the [[COVID-19 outbreak]], US President [[Donald Trump]] announces a travel ban from Europe's [[Schengen area]] to the United States from 13 March, for 30 days.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/air-transport/us-bans-travel-from-europe/137206.article |title= US bans all travel from Europe |author= Pilar Wolfsteller |date= 12 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref> Numerous other countries implement similar bans in the following days.\n\n; 17 March\n: [[Trans States Airlines]] announces it will shut down operations on 1 April amid the coronavirus crisis, nine months earlier than previously planned due to a pilot shortage and consolidation.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/strategy/trans-states-airlines-to-fold-in-april/137349.article |title= Trans States Airlines to fold in April |author= Pilar Wolfsteller |date= 17 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n; 18 March\n: The average daily number of flights in [[Eurocontrol]] airspace falls below half that of the previous year, due to [[travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/air-transport/european-flight-activity-halves-under-coronavirus-onslaught/137446.article |title= European flight activity halves under coronavirus onslaught |author= David Kaminski-Morrow |date= 20 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n; 19 March\n: [[Compass Airlines (North America)|Compass Airlines]], owned by Trans States Holdings and flying regional routes for [[American Airlines]] as [[American Eagle (airline brand)|American Eagle]] from Los Angeles, writes to its employees it will shut down completely on 7 April.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/strategy/compass-airlines-to-shut-down-operations/137408.article |title= Compass Airlines to shut down operations |author= Pilar Wolfsteller |date= 19 March 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n=== April ===\n\n; 15 April\n: As demand continues to collapse due to the [[impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on aviation]], over two-thirds of the worldwide fleet of 22,000 mainline passenger airliners are inactive, leaving 7,635 in operation. Europe is most affected, with less than 15% of aircraft operating, compared to 45% in North America and 49% in Asia (49%). A greater proportion of [[narrowbody aircraft]] are inactive (37%) than [[widebody aircraft]] (27%).<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/fleets/mixed-fortunes-globally-as-active-fleet-drops-towards-7000-aircraft/137893.article |title= Mixed fortunes globally as active fleet drops towards 7,000 aircraft |author= Max Kingsley-Jones |date= 15 April 2020 |work= Flightglobal}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Aviation timelines navbox}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in aviation| ]]\n[[Category:Aviation by year]]\n[[Category:2020-related lists]]\n[[Category:2020-related timelines]]\n[[Category:Technology timelines by year]]\n[[Category:Transport timelines by year]]\n", "name_user": "Marc Lacoste", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eApril:del excess \" (49%)\" + ref integrity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_in_aviation"}
